people just dont quite get it a little background about me i m a bi racial person black white i m disabled i attend college i want to make something of myself one day i am a thinker i felt those are important to note so you ll know where i m commin from i love my race both black and white i don t hate anyone mislike a few but don t we all i have a good circle of friends trying to get ahead in life no criminal record wheelchair sorta hampered me there lol but i need to get this off my chest whats up with these racists better yet what s up with these anti racists it s one thing if you re another brotha or sista but for the white people why do you feel the urge to try to fend for us aren t we capable of that ourselves martin luther king a great man malcom x another great man do you think we can t handle things on our own that we are uncapable my mother is black and beautiful my father a good white man you all don t understand and you never will mind yo own this isn t meant as disrespect to anyone but if you don t know how it is don t try to pretend you do i respect you all trying to help but i feel sometimes that the anti racists spew more hate then the racists do violence name calling etc my mamma always taught me be respectful no matter who you are talking to because we really don t know where they are coming from as we ve not walked in their shoes you all don t know how it was for me being raised as a bi racial kid people from both the black and white community shunned me school mates would not accept me because i was either too white or too black i m against multiculturalism i m an africanist i believe we need to go back to the mother land the land that gave us birth and fix what s being wronged black people suffering because of lack of education we as african americans need to step up to the plate sacrifice and give back to the land and the people who we call our own demarcus i agree with you you are trying to make something of your life and you don't use your disability as an excuse in life you sound like an intelligent young man with a bright future American Civil Rights Movement (1955-1968) Similarities between the Bible and the Qur'an Vernon Schillinger White supremacy Martin Luther King, Jr. Theory of conduct Kender Humphrey Bogart Social rule Episodes of Lost (Season 1) White nationalism Friends Malcolm X African American Jon Secada The Human Stain Confucius Current teachings of Prem Rawat Ten Commandments Jiddu Krishnamurti Shaggy dog story Socrates Kodocha Constitution of the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus Rosa Parks Anti-Mormonism American Psycho The Death Gate Cycle African American Vernacular English Epeli Ganilau Stoicism Time Out of Mind Cindy Sheehan Oz (TV series) Rich Mullins African American contemporary issues Practices of Jehovah's Witnesses About a Boy Blacks and Mormonism Chess strategy and tactics Afrocentrism Taxi Driver Justification (theology) Black nationalism Interracial couple The Amber Spyglass Comparing and contrasting Judaism and Christianity Nadir of American race relations Mojave people True Crime: Streets of LA Autism rights movement Skinhead Ty Cobb Reparations for slavery Porgy and Bess Abortion debate Boston Public Phoebe Buffay's songs Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints AFI 100 Years series Human sexual behavior EastEnders Equal Protection Clause Aesthetic Realism Sola fide The Smoking Room Desegregation Teen Girl Squad Montgomery Bus Boycott LaVeyan Satanism Sant Thakar Singh Theodicy The Catcher in the Rye American Civil Rights Movement (1896-1954) African American literature Avenue Q Trailer Park Boys The Lion, the Witch and the Wardrobe Ernst Z__ndel Sin City Passing Main characters of Fullmetal Alchemist Blonde on Blonde RuneScape quests Little Britain Goodness and value theory British National Party Soul Plame affair Michael Lerner (rabbi) 